Project Overview
Chicago Input Patch is an experimental WinMM proxy DLL designed to restore joystick compatibility in legacy Windows 95 / early DirectX era games (1995–1999) when running on modern Windows (10/11).
Many games from that period — such as Doom 95, Resident Evil (1996), Legacy of Kain: Soul Reaver, Street Fighter Alpha 2, and Samurai Shodown II — depend heavily on the legacy WinMM joystick APIs (joyGetNumDevs, joyGetDevCaps, joyGetPosEx, etc.).
On modern systems, the physical gameport hardware and its kernel driver (vjoyd.vxd) no longer exist, causing these games to:

Detect 0 joysticks
Return invalid or empty capabilities (JOYCAPS)
Fail initialization checks
Silently abort startup via ExitProcess(0)

This proxy DLL solves the problem by:

Intercepting key joystick and timer functions
Faking a classic analog gameport (returns 1 device + plausible capabilities)
Forwarding all non-intercepted WinMM functions to the real system winmm.dll
Preparing the ground for future USB controller redirection (XInput/DirectInput planned)

The name "Chicago" refers to the codename of Windows 95 — the era this patch targets.
Core Problem: Why Games Crash Silently
Doom 95 (and similar titles) performs strict startup checks in this approximate sequence (reconstructed from assembly behavior):
textcall joyGetNumDevs
test eax, eax
jz  fail_exit                ; if 0 devices → abort

push sizeof(JOYCAPSA)
push offset joycaps
push 0
call joyGetDevCapsA
test eax, eax
jnz fail_exit                ; if not MMSYSERR_NOERROR → abort

push offset joyinfoex
push 0
call joyGetPosEx
test eax, eax
jnz fail_exit                ; if not MMSYSERR_NOERROR → abort

; Additional validation
if (joycaps.wNumAxes == 0 || joycaps.wNumButtons == 0)
    ExitProcess(0)
Any failure (0 devices, invalid caps, error code) triggers an immediate ExitProcess(0) — no window, no message.
Other games (Resident Evil, Soul Reaver, etc.) are more tolerant and continue without joystick if detection fails.
Solution Architecture
The proxy works in three layers:

Load real WinMM
Dynamically load the original system winmm.dll (via full path to avoid loading loop).
Intercept critical functions
joyGetNumDevs → force return ≥1
joyGetDevCapsA/W → simulate classic gameport (2 axes, 4 buttons, 0–65535 range)
joyGetPosEx → return centered/neutral position (future: map USB input here)
Timer functions (timeGetTime, etc.) → forward or fallback to GetTickCount()

Forward everything else
All other ~180 exports (audio, MIDI, MCI, aux, etc.) are forwarded transparently to the real DLL.

No winmm_real.dll in game folder (optional advanced mode)
Instead of requiring the user to rename/copy the original DLL, the proxy can load it directly from the system directory:
C++char sysPath[MAX_PATH];
GetSystemDirectoryA(sysPath, MAX_PATH);
strcat_s(sysPath, "\\winmm.dll");
realWinMM = LoadLibraryA(sysPath);
This makes installation simpler: just drop the proxy winmm.dll in the game folder.
Key Implementation Details
Fake Joystick (Critical for Doom 95)
C++UINT WINAPI joyGetNumDevs(void) {
    return real_joyGetNumDevs ? real_joyGetNumDevs() : 1;  // Force ≥1
}

MMRESULT WINAPI joyGetDevCapsA(UINT id, LPJOYCAPSA caps, UINT size) {
    if (real_joyGetDevCapsA) return real_joyGetDevCapsA(id, caps, size);
    ZeroMemory(caps, sizeof(JOYCAPSA));
    strcpy_s(caps->szPname, "Emulated Gameport");
    caps->wNumAxes    = 2;
    caps->wNumButtons = 4;
    caps->wXmin = caps->wYmin = 0;
    caps->wXmax = caps->wYmax = 65535;
    return MMSYSERR_NOERROR;
}
